				By William Alden			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-07T17:44:08+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 7, 2014 1:44 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 7, 2014 1:44 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/07/legal-costs-weighed-on-wall-streets-first-half-profits/" data-title="Legal Costs Weighed on Wall Street&#8217;s First-Half Profits" data-description="Wall Street firms&#039; profit declined 13 percent from results in the period a year earlier, according to a report on Tuesday by the New York State comptroller.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/08/business/dbpix-wall2/dbpix-wall2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/08/business/dbpix-wall2/dbpix-wall2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/08/business/dbpix-wall2/dbpix-wall2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003162272" width="480" height="262" alt="Wall Street profits have declined in part from legal settlements, according to the comptroller for New York State."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="262"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Wall Street profits have declined in part from legal settlements, according to the comptroller for New York State.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mario Tama/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.osc.state.ny.us/osdc/rpt9-2015.pdf">Document: New York Comptroller&#8217;s Report (PDF)</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Wall Street has long been a chief source of tax revenue for New York State. But the revenue machine is faltering.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Wall Street firms earned $8.7 billion in profit in the first half of the year, a 13 percent decline from results in the period a year earlier, according to a report on Tuesday by the New York State comptroller, Thomas P. DiNapoli. The trend suggests profit for the full year may not exceed last yearâs level of $16.7 billion, which itself was a 30 percent decline from 2012, the report said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A main reason for the declines has been the legal settlements banks have struck to resolve issues stemming from the financial crisis. Since the beginning of 2009, the six largest bank holding companies have agreed to pay $130 billion in settlement costs, the comptrollerâs office said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even as profits are being strained, however, the state has also been a beneficiary of some of the legal settlements. The state expects to receive $4.5 billion in settlement payments in the current fiscal year, including $3.6 billion from a <a title="Related DealBook article." href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/30/bnp-paribas-pleads-guilty-in-sanctions-case/">settlement</a> with BNP Paribas and $715 million from a <a title="Related DealBook article." href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/credit-suisse-set-to-plead-guilty-in-tax-evasion-case/">deal with</a> Credit Suisse.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Wall Street remains very profitable, but earnings may be constrained this year as the industry pays a price for behavior that contributed to the financial crisis,â Mr. DiNapoli said in a statement. &#8220;While the securities industry in New York City has a smaller employment base than before the financial crisis, it remains an important part of the economy and a major contributor to state and city budgets.&#8221;</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/08/business/dbpix-wall1/dbpix-wall1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/08/business/dbpix-wall1/dbpix-wall1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/08/business/dbpix-wall1/dbpix-wall1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003162260" width="480" height="376" alt="Thomas P. DiNapoli, the comptroller for New York State, examined the health of New York&#039;s financial industry."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="376"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Thomas P. DiNapoli, the comptroller for New York State, examined the health of New York's financial industry.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mike Groll/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When profits rise or fall on Wall Street, a range of businesses in New York City &#8212; from restaurants to luxury real estate &#8212; feels the effects. But when it comes to tax revenue, the swings on Wall Street more heavily affect the state, which relies more on personal and business taxes than the city does. New York State also collects taxes from Wall Street employees who live in the suburbs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the fiscal year running from April 2013 through March 2014, taxes related to Wall Street accounted for 19 percent of New York Stateâs tax collections, the report said. That level, an increase from 16 percent in the previous year, was augmented by the one-time effects of taxpayers shifting their income in response to higher federal tax rates. The comptrollerâs office said it expected tax revenue from Wall Street to fall in the current fiscal year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The decline could continue. Wall Street lost 2,600 jobs in the city in the 12 months through August, the report said. Compared with its size before the crisis, Wall Street is now 15 percent smaller, with 162,400 jobs as of August.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bonuses, however, may continue to go up. The comptrollerâs office <a title="Related DealBook article." href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/03/12/wall-street-bonuses-go-up-as-the-number-of-jobs-goes-down/">estimated in March</a> that the average bonus on Wall Street rose 15 percent in 2013 to the highest level since the crisis, partially as a result of deferred compensation being paid out.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âCurrent compensation trends suggest bonuses could increase in 2014 for the third consecutive year,â the report said.</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 10/08/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">B</span><span itemprop="printPage">5</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: Decline on Wall St..</p>    </div>
</footer>
	</div>
